title: For Sale/Trade:  NEF Survival Handi Rifle .223
postcontent: For sale or trade - New England Firearms Handi-Rifle chambered in .223 with bull barrel and survival tactical stock.  You can easily fit a box of 20 rounds in the buttstock along with a cleaning snake.  Also, the foregrip has a quick removal screw and storage for cleaning patches or whatever else.  The compartments are not waterproof and the rifle is a single shot rifle.  The scope was maybe $110.00 new a few years back, it isn't expensive but has done a fine job on this rifle.  I put a few target rounds thru it to test it out every so often and have rarely had to make adjustments to the scope.I was told that NEF is no longer manufacturing this rifle or other versions of it.  It really is a neat little package that has been awsome for everything from prarie dogs out west to coyotes and foxes.  I zeroed in the scope at 150 yards and eliminated the need for hold over out to 200 yards.  I hit about 1/2" high at 100 yards and 2" low at 200 useing the standard 55 grain round.  I have used all types of ammo and they all preform well.  The only issue I have ever encountered was a 90 degree day shooting prarie dogs in New Mexico and I had to let the barrel cool after a couple boxes of steel cased rounds.  The barrel was pretty hot.Rifle is going for $350 new on gunbroker or around $300 used.  If you buy online you pay shipping and transfer fee which adds up to about $50 extra.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Winchester 9422 - .22lr - $850
postcontent:
This Winchester 9422 is, unsurprisingly, a .22lr version of the famous Model 94.  Introduced in 1972 it was Winchester's flagship .22 rifle, made on modern manufacturing machines and meant to help restore their flagging reputation.  Production ended in 2005.
This one was purchased new in 1973 by my father, who told me he'd not put more than 150 rounds through it.  I've probably fired it less than 50 times myself since inheriting it.  It's a fabulous shooter.  A fun, accurate cowboy rifle, without the kick or the cost of a full caliber.  It can handle .22lr as well as .22 Long and .22 Short.  It will NOT fire .22 Magnum.
This rifle is about as close to mint as you can get.   The stock, receiver, and barrel are all pristine with no blemishes or discoloration. 
Unfortunately, no original box, but it does come with an early-70's vintage soft case and a printed version of the factory manual.
$850
I comply with all IL firearm transfer laws, so this sale will require a FOID check and a single day longarm waiting period.Thanks for looking,Doug

title: For Sale:  Very rare 1936 Belgium Browning "test market only" sweet 16 with matching 2nd barrel
postcontent: This is a very rare 1936 "test market only" sweet 16. The sweet 16 was released into the general public in 1937, however the gun was release to a limited test market in 1936. This makes this browning very rare due to the already low production numbers of the 1936 16 gauge shotguns (around 2300 total) Very few true 1936 browning sweet 16 shotguns still exist today. Before emailing me saying this is not a sweet 16 because it is not stamp please do your research. "sweet 16" was not stamped on the guns until the 40's. The 1936 and early 1937 models also do not all have the gold trigger or safety. The only way to prove this year is by narrowing the gun down by the serial number, inspecting the ejector portion of the receiver, and looking at the factory installed barrel to see if it has the holes drilled out of the barrel ring. I have done my research and had several browning enthusiast go through this firearm to verify it is a sweet 16. The gun appears to be all original, all numbers match on receiver and both barrels. Sometime post war the gun was shipped backed to browning to be converted from 2 9/16 shell to 2 and 3/4. Browning stamped the conversion marks on the barrel. This is one of the few modifications that raise the value of the gun. wood finish is in amazing shape. receiver and barrels are all in great shape for age. Barrels have not been altered. The original finish looks great with minimal wear for the age. If the gun was 99% I would be asking three times more for the gun. Email me for any and all details, price is very firm at 1,000. Not only is this a numbers matching 2 barrel set, but it is also a sweet 16. my price is more than fair. By the way, the serial number is 104332 on the receiver, and both barrels.
